lities after breakups are driven by the same three mechanisms: access to the law and justice, interactions with legal professionals, and the ways these two factors shape lifestyle and standard of living. Family Law in Action is a rigorous but compassionate study that encourages governments to make good on the emancipatory promise enshrined in divorce law.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDivorcexLaw and legislationzFrance. 0aDivorcexLaw and legislationzQuébec (Province). 0aDomestic relationszFrance. 0aDomestic relationszQuébec (Province). 7aLAW / Family Law / Divorce & Separation.2bisacsh1 aFryberger, Annelies, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichmond Mouillot, Miranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311140824840uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077486649140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774866491423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774866491/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-140824-8  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packageb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles